        <div class="msgSubject">UI suggestion: color-coded Wear on equipment slots</div>
        <div class="sm notbold">
          
          Posted: 2010-11-17 18:53:14 | Edited: Nov 18 2010  2:47pm  | <input type="checkbox" name="quote-129004159468316857" id="quote-129004159468316857" class="msgQuoteCheck" onchange="multiQuote2()"/><label for="quote-129004159468316857" onclick="multiQuote2()"> Quote</label>  | <a href="/forum.html?forum=173&amp;mid=129004159468316857&amp;post=1&amp;replyto=129004159468316857&amp;page=1" class="icon-replytothis" rel="nofollow">Reply to Post</a> | <a id="FOLLOW_MID_129004159468316857" onclick="followToggle('add','129004159468316857')" href="javascript:" class="icon-follow">Follow</a> 
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="msgWhoFrame">
        <div class="msgUM"><a class="msgWhoName " href="/users/Rhianu">Rhianu</a></div><div class="msgAvatar"></div><div class="msgStar"><img src="http://common.zam.com/shared/s2.gif" alt="*"/><img src="http://common.zam.com/shared/s2.gif" alt="*"/></div><div class="msgWhoNum">297 posts</div>
        <div class="msgScore">
          Score: Excellent  
          <div class="msgRatings"></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="msgContentFrame">So I was doing some Guildleves today, and after doing a couple mining Leves I noticed a new status icon I had never seen before had appeared at the top of my screen. So I highlight it to get more information, and am met with this message: <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig">&quot;Certain gear is damaged, diminishing its properties.&quot;</div></div> <br /> <br /><i>&quot;Really?&quot;</i> I think to myself. <i>&quot;My gear is damaged? That's what that icon means? Well okay, I guess I'll need to go repair it. Now which piece of gear is it that needs repaired?&quot;</i> <br /> <br />I open up my <u>Attributes &amp; Gear</u> menu, and start looking through my equipment. <i>&quot;Could it be my Garlond Goggles?&quot;</i> I click on them and check the Wear value. It reads 7527/13900. <i>&quot;Is that's what causing it?&quot;</i> I quickly round down the number in my mind to make them easier to deal with. <i>&quot;Okay, 7,500 out of 13,900. That's like 7.5 out of 13.9. Not too bad, I guess. Maybe it's something else.&quot;</i> I start checking through my other gear, and decide to look at the Bone Ring I have equipped. The Wear is 4564/6210, or 4.5 out of 6.2. <i>&quot;Hmm, that doesn't seem to be so bad, either. Which piece could it be that's causing the damaged gear icon to appear?&quot;</i> I begin looking through my gear once more. <br /> <br /><i>&quot;It couldn't be that new Copper Choker I just made. That's brand new.&quot;</i> But I check it anyway. 8280/8280. <i>&quot;Just as I thought. No damage at all.&quot;</i> But then which piece of equipment WAS damaged enough to the point it needed repairs? <i>&quot;Not my Asuran Armguards!&quot;</i> I think. <i>&quot;I got those with FFXIII!&quot;</i> I check the armguards. 6867/13900. <i>&quot;Is that it? How damaged does a piece of equipment need to be before it needs repairs?&quot;</i> I had no idea. <br /> <br />So I begin to unequip everything, hoping that I can figure it out by a process of elimination. Whenever the icon disappears, whichever piece of gear I unequipped immediately prior should be the damaged piece. Or so I thought. <br /> <br />I strip down completely, my character wearing nothing but an undershirt and a pair of undergarments, neither of which can be unequipped, and the icon is still there. However, I do still have a Weathered Pickaxe strapped to my back. I check its Wear value. 88782/97600. I switch the pickaxe out for a Weathered Gladius. 80494/87840. <i>&quot;Can't be that.&quot;</i> So I examine my undershirt. 2538/5520. <i>&quot;Maybe the undergarments, then?&quot;</i> 2977/5520. <br /> <br /><i>&quot;Is it accumulative? Do I need to repair ALL my gear? This is so confusing.&quot;</i> <br /> <br />[---] <br /> <br />Checking the Wear value of gear is a huge problem with FFXIV, and it needs to be fixed. In World of Warcraft, when you have damaged gear, a little &quot;paper doll&quot; appears on your screen, with highlighted equipment making it easy to tell at a glance which piece is damaged. Of course this particular UI feature works fine for WoW, but it might not be the best solution for FFXIV. So instead, I propose adding color-coded highlights to equipped gear in the equipment screen, as depicted in the following image, which I made in Photoshop: <br /> <br /><a href="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v255/snuuj/FFXIV/interface_redesign/gear_wear.png" title="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v255/snuuj/FFXIV/interface_redesign/gear_wear.png" rel="external nofollow">http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v255/snuuj/FFXIV/interface_redesign/gear_wear.png</a> <br /> <br />Under this system, any gear which is damaged to a certain point becomes highlighted with a color corresponding to the level of damage. Items which are only slightly damaged are highlighted yellow, items with moderate damage are highlighted orange, and items that are critically damaged are highlighted in crimson red. Also, a text-overlay indicating the exact percentage of Wear for that item will appear over any damaged items, thus making it easy to see exactly which of your equipped items are damaged, and just how badly damaged they are, as well as making it easy to compare the damage between items, all without having to do any menu searching at all. And since Wear is depicted as a percentage here rather than a convoluted and unnecessarily high number, you wouldn't have to do any rounding or figuring in your head, either. <br /> <br />If this idea were implemented, the problem with checking the Wear on your gear would be almost completely solved. Maybe just add some similar color coding to items in your inventory, and we'd be set. <br /> <br /> <br /><b><span style="color:Red">EDIT:</span></b> After talking with some people, someone suggested the idea of HP bars instead of text, so I made this alternative design: <br /> <br /><a href="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v255/snuuj/FFXIV/interface_redesign/gear_wear2.png" title="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v255/snuuj/FFXIV/interface_redesign/gear_wear2.png" rel="external nofollow">http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v255/snuuj/FFXIV/interface_redesign/gear_wear2.png</a> <br /> <br />The box-radial layout of the HP bars was inspired by SE's iPhone game, <a href="HTTP://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-3WI_tZEukI" rel="external nofollow" title="www.youtube.com/watch?v=-3WI_tZEukI">Hills and Rivers Remain</a>. <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Nov 18th 2010  3:47pm by Rhianu </span></i></div>
